\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf3 APPLIED MACHINE LEARNING \'a0\'b7\'a0 SPRING 2026\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\sa400\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs48 \AppleTypeServices \cf2 MeterMind: Symbolic vs Learned Approaches to Metrical Compression in Iambic Pentameter\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl504\sa400\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf3 Andrew Li, Alexandra Jing\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl544\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf3 We investigate whether symbolic rule-based constraint-solving, learned neural sequence models, or large pretrained language models best handle the task of metrical compression, taking expanded archaic prose and rewriting it into iambic pentameter. Using Shakespeare's 154 sonnets as a corpus, we train and evaluate three models (a DP reorderer, a GRU with Bahdanau attention, and Claude Haiku) on three metrics: Metrical Accuracy (MA), Semantic Preservation (SP), and Grammaticality (G). We find that the symbolic DP reorderer leads on Metrical Accuracy (MA = 0.9996 \'b1 0.0064) and Semantic Preservation (SP = 0.9847 \'b1 0.0207) by construction, while Claude Haiku achieves the strongest Grammaticality score (G = 0.1475 \'b1 0.0246) and competitive MA (0.8680 \'b1 0.1600) and SP (0.8540 \'b1 0.1020) with no task-specific training. The GRU with Bahdanau attention substantially underperforms both baselines across all metrics (MA = 0.5476, SP = 0.2622, G = 0.0971), potentially reflecting severe overfitting on a dataset of only 1,164 training pairs. \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl396\sa240\partightenfactor0

