\f2\b\fs32\fsmilli16200 \cf2 1. Introduction\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl612\sa400\partightenfactor0

\f3\b0\fs34 \cf2 Iambic pentameter \'97 the 
\f4\i da-DUM da-DUM da-DUM da-DUM da-DUM
\f3\i0  rhythm of Shakespeare, Milton, and Keats \'97 is one of the most studied metrical forms in English literature. Its ten-syllable alternating stress pattern is simple to define but surprisingly difficult to produce. This tension makes iambic pentameter a compelling testbed for machine learning. The task requires simultaneously satisfying a hard phonological constraint (stress pattern), a soft semantic constraint (preserve meaning), and an implicit fluency constraint (sound like natural language). These three objectives often pull in different directions. \
We frame the problem as metrical compression: given an expanded archaic prose version of a Shakespeare sonnet line, containing all the original words plus filler, can a model recover the compressed, metrically regular original? This controlled setup lets us isolate the metrical learning signal from the confound of vocabulary or register translation. \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl612\partightenfactor0
\cf2 Our central hypothesis is: 
\f2\b symbolic stress constraints outperform learned approaches on Metrical Accuracy, but underperform on Semantic Preservation and Grammaticality, because explicit rule-following cannot model the contextual trade-offs that learned models capture.
\f3\b0  \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl583\sa400\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs32\fsmilli16200 \cf2 2. Related Work\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl432\sa200\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs24 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf2 Poetry generation with formal constraints\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl612\sa400\partightenfactor0

\f3\b0\fs34 \AppleTypeServices \cf2 Generating formal verse poetry with strict constraints on meter, rhyme, and alliteration has been a long-standing challenge in NLP. The most directly relevant prior work is ByGPT5 (Belouadi & Eger, 2023), which argues for end-to-end style-conditioned poetry generation without hand-crafted constraints. The authors identify two failure modes of prior end-to-end attempts: insufficient training data, and a mismatch between subword tokenization and character-level poetic styles such as meter and rhyme. Their solution is ByGPT5, a token-free decoder-only transformer pre-trained at the byte level and fine-tuned on QuaTrain, a machine-labeled corpus of over 2.7 million English quatrains. ByGPT5 outperforms GPT-2, mT5, and ChatGPT on meter, rhyme, and alliteration scores, and achieves performance comparable to human poets on meter in human evaluation. Crucially, Belouadi and Eger find that meter \'97 being a syllable-level style \'97 is learnable by subword models too, but that token-free models have a systematic advantage. Their finding that end-to-end approaches can match symbolic pipelines on meter directly motivates our investigation: we ask whether this holds when the vocabulary is severely constrained (archaic Shakespearean English) and the task is framed as compression rather than open-ended generation. \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl432\sa200\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs24 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf2 Seq2seq with attention\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl612\sa400\partightenfactor0

\f3\b0\fs34 \AppleTypeServices \cf2 Our Model 2 is built on the encoder-decoder framework with Bahdanau attention (Bahdanau, Cho & Bengio, 2015), the foundational architecture for learned sequence-to-sequence transduction. Bahdanau et al. identified a critical bottleneck in the basic encoder-decoder approach: compressing a variable-length source into a single fixed-length vector degrades performance on long sequences. Their solution, allowing the decoder to compute a soft alignment over all encoder hidden states at each generation step, is particularly well-motivated for our reordering task. When generating position 
\f4\i i
\f3\i0  of the output, the attention mechanism can in principle learn to focus on whichever input word belongs at that position, effectively learning a soft permutation. This maps directly onto what our symbolic DP reorderer does explicitly, making the attention GRU a natural learned counterpart to the rule-based baseline. \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl432\sa200\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs24 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf2 Constrained text generation\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl612\sa400\partightenfactor0

\f3\b0\fs34 \AppleTypeServices \cf2 A consistent finding across poetry generation literature is that unconstrained neural models struggle to satisfy hard phonological constraints from data alone. Hopkins and Kiela (2017) used Weighted Finite State Transducers to enforce metric constraints and roll back generation on violations. Van de Cruys (2020) modified output probability distributions directly to bias generation toward desired stress patterns. Our copy mask which restricts the GRU decoder's output vocabulary to words present in the source input is a form of hard lexical constraint at inference time. Belouadi and Eger (2023) note that such prior knowledge injection, while effective, introduces cascading errors when constraints interact and limits the model's ability to learn holistic trade-offs. Our ablation (Ablation 2) directly tests this: does the copy constraint help or hinder the GRU's ability to produce metrically and semantically appropriate output? \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl432\sa200\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs24 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf2 Computational meter and the CMU Pronouncing Dictionary\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl612\sa400\partightenfactor0

\f3\b0\fs34 \AppleTypeServices \cf2 Automated metrical analysis relies on mapping orthographic words to their phonemic stress patterns. The standard tool for this in English NLP is the CMU Pronouncing Dictionary, a hand-compiled lexicon of over 125,000 words with phonetic transcriptions encoding primary stress (1), secondary stress (2), and unstressed (0) syllables (Mehra & Susan, 2020). We use CMU as the backbone of our Metrical Accuracy metric and our DP reorderer. A known limitation, directly relevant to our corpus, is that CMU covers modern English and is incomplete for archaic verb forms. Words like 
\f4\i feedest
\f3\i0  and 
\f4\i makest
\f3\i0  \'97 produced by our elision expansion pipeline \'97 are absent from CMU, requiring a fallback strategy of stripping the archaic 
\f4\i -est
\f3\i0  and 
\f4\i -eth
\f3\i0  suffixes and looking up the verbal root. Mehra and Susan demonstrate that CMU-based phoneme extraction is robust for standard English but degrades on out-of-vocabulary words, a limitation we acknowledge in our evaluation. \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl432\sa200\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs24 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf2 Evaluation metrics: semantic similarity and grammaticality\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl612\sa400\partightenfactor0

\f3\b0\fs34 \AppleTypeServices \cf2 Our Semantic Preservation metric uses cosine similarity between SBERT embeddings (Reimers & Gurevych, 2019). Standard BERT embeddings are unsuitable for this purpose: Reimers and Gurevych demonstrate that averaging BERT output layers yields an average Spearman correlation of only 54.81 on semantic textual similarity tasks \'97 worse than averaging GloVe embeddings. SBERT addresses this by fine-tuning BERT in a siamese network architecture on natural language inference data, producing embeddings where semantically similar sentences are geometrically close in vector space and can be meaningfully compared with cosine similarity. SBERT achieves an average Spearman correlation of 74.89 across seven STS benchmarks, outperforming prior sentence embedding methods by 11.7 points. Cosine similarity between SBERT embeddings is therefore a principled and well-validated measure of semantic preservation \'97 the degree to which the meaning of the output line matches the input prose. \
Our Grammaticality metric uses GPT-2 perplexity (Radford et al., 2019), normalised as 
\f4\i G = 1 / (1 + log(perplexity))
\f3\i0 . Radford et al. show that GPT-2, trained on 40GB of diverse web text, achieves state-of-the-art performance on 7 out of 8 language modeling benchmarks in a zero-shot setting, establishing it as a robust proxy for naturalness and fluency across domains. Lower perplexity indicates text that is more consistent with the language distributions GPT-2 learned, which we use as a proxy for grammaticality and fluency. We acknowledge a known limitation: GPT-2 was trained on modern English and will systematically assign higher perplexity to archaic register (thee, thou, doth) regardless of grammatical correctness within Early Modern English. This means our G scores may underestimate the true fluency of model outputs that successfully preserve Shakespearean register, which is a limitation we discuss in Section 10. \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl432\sa200\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs24 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf2 Pretrained LLMs as a comparison point\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl612\partightenfactor0

\f3\b0\fs34 \AppleTypeServices \cf2 Our three models represent three fundamentally different paradigms for the metrical compression task: symbolic rule-following (DP), task-specific learning from examples (GRU), and implicit knowledge transfer from pretraining (Claude). The third paradigm is motivated by a key question: does broad exposure to text including poetry, without any task-specific training, transfer to a highly constrained structured generation task? This is a meaningful research question independent of which specific LLM is used. Claude Haiku, as a large pretrained language model, has been exposed to vast quantities of English poetry during pretraining and has implicit knowledge of iambic meter, stress patterns, and Shakespearean register. Prompting it zero-shot tests the ceiling of what pretrained knowledge alone can achieve on this task, providing a natural upper-bound comparison for both the symbolic and learned baselines. \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl583\sa400\partightenfactor0

