\f2\b\fs32\fsmilli16200 \cf2 4. Dataset\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl612\sa400\partightenfactor0

\f3\b0\fs34 \cf2 We use Shakespeare's 154 sonnets from Project Gutenberg as our poetry corpus. After stripping Gutenberg headers and Roman numeral sonnet headings, the corpus yields 2,155 lines. Elisions common in Early Modern English (
\f4\i Feed'st
\f3\i0 , 
\f4\i distill'd
\f3\i0 , 
\f4\i o'er
\f3\i0 ) were expanded to their full forms using 14 regex rules operating on Unicode-normalised text, producing a clean line corpus with no apostrophe contractions. \
Each line was then expanded into three distinct archaic prose paraphrases using Claude Haiku via the Anthropic API. The prompt required all original words to appear verbatim in the expansion while preserving archaic register (thee, thou, doth, hath). Expansions failing word-presence validation were retried and discarded if still invalid, yielding 
\f2\b 1,455 valid (input, target) pairs out of 6,465, 
\f3\b0 so roughly 2/3rds of the lines failed. The most likely cause is the model consistently dropping small words like a, the, and, in form the expansions, which trips up validator even when expansion is otherwise good. We\'92ve also programmed it to rerun batch of three if a single expansion fails, so that also may have contributed to the problem. Regardless, the dataset was split 80/10/10 on unique target lines to prevent data leakage across splits. \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

