\f3\fs34 \cf2 Attention wins decisively on MA (+0.2864) and meaningfully on SP (+0.0488). The plain GRU's marginally better G score is not a sign of higher quality: without attention, the model appears to generate shorter, simpler, more modern-sounding sequences that happen to score lower perplexity under GPT-2, which was trained on modern English. This is precisely the confound identified in Section 3, that G is an unreliable discriminator for archaic text. Both models exhibit severe overfitting: by epoch 50 training loss reaches 0.0569 while validation loss climbs to 8.36 for the plain GRU (best val loss 6.265), confirming that 1,164 training pairs is insufficient for this task regardless of architecture. \
We re-ran GRU inference on the test set without the source vocabulary mask, allowing the model to generate any word in its vocabulary. No retraining was needed. Results are shown in Figure 5 and the table below. \

