\f2\b\fs32\fsmilli16200 \cf2 10. Limitations\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl612\sa400\partightenfactor0

\f3\b0\fs34 \cf2 Several limitations bound the scope of our conclusions. First, the dataset is small: 1,455 training pairs drawn from a single author's work limits generalisability. The 77% validation filter failure rate during data generation suggests the LLM expansion task is harder than anticipated and may have introduced systematic bias toward simpler lines, since we were originally drawing from a 6,465 pairs. \
Second, the archaic vocabulary of the training corpus means the GRU's learned representations are narrow \'97 performance on modern prose is expected to degrade significantly. The demo section illustrates this; the copy mask partially mitigates but does not eliminate out-of-vocabulary issues. \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl612\partightenfactor0
\cf2 Third, the Grammaticality metric (GPT-2 perplexity) was trained on modern English and systematically disadvantages archaic outputs regardless of their actual linguistic quality within the Early Modern English register. \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl583\sa400\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs32\fsmilli16200 \cf2 11. Conclusion\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl612\sa400\partightenfactor0

\f3\b0\fs34 \cf2 We set out to test whether symbolic rule-based constraint-solving, learned neural sequence models, or large pretrained language models best handle metrical compression into iambic pentameter. Our central hypothesis \'97 that symbolic approaches would lead on Metrical Accuracy but underperform on Semantic Preservation and Grammaticality \'97 was partially confirmed, but with a significant revision: the LLM baseline came far closer to the symbolic system than anticipated, while the learned GRU baseline fell far below both. \
The most surprising finding is the magnitude of Claude Haiku's zero-shot performance. With no task-specific training, Claude achieves SP = 0.854 \'97 a result the GRU, trained on 1,164 (input, target) pairs, cannot approach. This suggests that for highly constrained structured generation tasks with small training sets, a prompted LLM is not merely a convenient baseline but a genuinely competitive method. The GRU result, meanwhile, illustrates how rapidly seq2seq models can overfit on narrow corpora: the model learns the stress register of Shakespearean English but not the meaning-preserving reordering function it is trained to perform. \
Were we to repeat this project, we would focus on three changes. First, expand the dataset significantly \'97 either by sourcing additional Early Modern English poetry or by using LLM-generated synthetic pairs more aggressively. Second, replace GPT-2 with a domain-appropriate language model (fine-tuned on EEBO or similar) to obtain a meaningful Grammaticality signal. Third, investigate whether fine-tuning Claude on the task, rather than prompting it zero-shot, improves or hurts performance given the small dataset. \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl612\partightenfactor0
\cf2 Future work could extend this framework to other metrical forms (ballad meter, alexandrine, haiku syllabic constraints) to test whether the same paradigm rankings hold across constraint types. The metrical compression framing \'97 where the target vocabulary is constrained to source words \'97 also provides a clean experimental design that could be reused for studying other structured rewriting tasks. \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl583\sa400\partightenfactor0

